pullRequest.body:
Another step towards proving that a non-empty the real interval $[x,y]$ has boundary ${ x,y }$ (as a manifold).

Add missing `Icc.coe_top` and `Icc.coe_bot` lemmas.

---

### PR summary [8b314e3102](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15891/commits/8b314e3102918b1a82199fff9848f9db9f9a6a42)

#### Import changes for modified files

No significant changes to the import graph

|Files|Import difference|
|-|-|

</details>

---

<details><summary>

#### Declarations diff

</summary>

`+ IccLeftChart_extend_bot`
`+ IccLeftChart_extend_bot_mem_frontier`
`+ IccLeftChart_extend_interior_pos`
`+ IccRightChart_extend_right_mem_frontier`
`+ IccRightChart_extend_top`
`+ coe_bot`
`+ coe_top`
`+ iccLeftChart_extend_zero`
`+ modelWithCornersEuclideanHalfSpace_zero`
<details>
  <summary>You can run this locally as follows</summary>


```bash
## summary with just the declaration names:
./scripts/declarations_diff.sh <optional_commit>

## more verbose report:

```
</details>

The doc-module for `script/declarations_diff.sh` contains some details about this script.

</details>

---

<details><summary>No changes to technical debt.</summary>

You can run this locally as
```
./scripts/technical-debt-metrics.sh pr_summary
```
* The `relative` value is the weighted *sum* of the differences with weight given by the *inverse* of the current value of the statistic.
* The `absolute` value is the `relative` value divided by the total sum of the inverses of the current values (i.e. the weighted *average* of the differences).
</details>

@YaelDillies In this PR, I'm adding definitions for "the left endpoint of `Icc a b`, as a term of type `Icc a b`" (and similar). I'm not perfectly happy with the naming `left` and `right` for the endpoints; there is one place in this PR where I had to fix a name conflict. Do you have ideas for a better name?

Isn't that just `⊥` and `⊤`? See `Set.Icc.orderBot` and `Set.Icc.orderTop`.

One should check the performance is not too bad, but making `Set.Icc.orderBot` and `Set.Icc.orderTop` instances taking in `Fact (a ≤ b)` sounds reasonable, and well-motivated by your use-case.
Thanks for pointing this out! I'll take a look.
I checked: `Order/LatticeIntervals.lean` in fact contains such instances by now, so there was in fact nothing to do for me.
Thanks for the nits; comments addressed.
I'm open to the argument that this lemma (and its right counterpart) is sufficiently trivial to be inlined.
This has nothing to do with the manifold setup. Shouldn't this be available to anyone working with the set `Icc`?
Good point: I moved this next to the definition of `Set.Icc`. The names `Icc.left` and `Icc.right` might cause conflicts; if you prefer a different name, I'm open to changing it.

I'd appreciate help with this question: I'm not sure how to solve this. Removing `hxy_twice`, even if writing `include hxy in` before the theorem, yields an error "failed to synthesize Fact (x ≤ y)".

The same issue appears three more times below.
@YaelDillies I know you're not a differential geometer, but since you're looking right now: do you happen to know the answer? This is just a Lean question, I presume.
Maybe an instance `Fact (a < b) -> Fact (a <= b)` is sensible
Btw please include more context by making a multiline comment next time. It's really painful to navigate from this comment to the relevant piece of code on mobile
Sorry, I'll try to include more context next time. Thanks for the tip, the solution worked (I made it a scoped instance).
This should be `0 <`, right? And do you really need all the parentheses?
I do not; changed.
Seems like there's a lot of `rfl`s doing the heavy lifting. Are we missing API?
I've fixed all but three rfls; those seem to be missing API/ I certainly can't find them. Help finding those is welcome.
I have added these lemmas as helper results now.
Why do you need the spelling `Icc.instOrderBotElem.bot`? Is there a way to make that a bit nicer?
Thanks for making me check: there is a nicer way. Changed.

Do you need the brackets here?
```suggestion
    𝓡∂ n ⟨fun _ ↦ 0, by norm_num⟩ = 0 := rfl
```
I do, otherwise Lean complains `function expected`. (The notation 𝓡∂ takes exactly one argument.)
That sounds like a missing `withOverApp` or something like that. Can you start a topic on Zulip?

Why is this not
```suggestion
    (𝓡∂ n) 0 = 0 := rfl
```

This would yield `failed to synthesize
  OfNat (EuclideanHalfSpace n) 0`
Wait, the Euclidean half plane doesn't have a zero currently?!

```suggestion
lemma IccLeftChart_extend_bot : (IccLeftChart x y).extend (𝓡∂ 1) ⊥ = 0 := by
```

```suggestion
    0 < (IccLeftChart x y).extend (𝓡∂ 1) p 0 := by
```

```suggestion
lemma IccLeftChart_extend_bot_mem_frontier :
    (IccLeftChart x y).extend (𝓡∂ 1) ⊥ ∈ frontier (range (𝓡∂ 1)) := by
```

```suggestion
lemma IccRightChart_extend_top :
    (IccRightChart x y).extend (𝓡∂ 1) ⊤ = 0 := by
```

```suggestion
lemma IccRightChart_extend_top_mem_frontier :
    (IccRightChart x y).extend (𝓡∂ 1) ⊤ ∈ frontier (range (𝓡∂ 1)) := by
```

```suggestion
@[simp, norm_cast]
theorem coe_bot : ↑(⊥ : Icc a b) = a := rfl
```

```suggestion
@[simp, norm_cast]
theorem coe_top : ↑(⊤ : Icc a b) = b := rfl
```

pullRequest.title: feat: lemmas about the left and right boundary point under `Icc{Left,Right}Chart`
